(14, 'caretta', 'caretta', '', 'loggerhead sea turtle', '', '', '', 'testudines', 'turtles', 'loggerhead sea turtles', '', 'testudines', 'rafinesque', 'linnaeus', '{&quot;1814&quot;:&quot;1758&quot;}', '', 'We have returned to the use of &ldquo;sea turtles&rdquo; (rather than &ldquo;seaturtles&rdquo;) as part of the standard English name for marine turtles.  The combined name has not been used recently in the literature.', 'michelle koo', 'John B. Iverson (Chair), Peter A. Meylan, Michael E. Seidel', '', 0, 0, 0),
(15, 'chelonia', 'mydas', '', 'green sea turtle', '', '', '', 'testudines', 'turtles', 'green sea turtles', '', 'testudines', 'brongniart', 'linnaeus', '{&quot;1800&quot;:&quot;1758&quot;}', '', 'The Black Turtle of the Pacific Ocean has been considered a separate species (*Chelonia agassizii*) by some authors (e.g., Pritchard and Trebbau, 1984, SSAR Contrib. Herpetol. 2: 1&ndash;403), a subspecies of *Chelonia mydas* by others (Kamezaki and Matsui, 1995, J. Herpetol. 29: 51&ndash;60), and synonymous with *Chelonia mydas* by others (e.g., Bowen et al., 1992, Evolution 46: 865&ndash;881).  We follow Parham and Zug (1996, Marine Turtle Newsl. 72: 2&ndash;5) and Karl and Bowen (1999, Cons. Biol. 13: 990&ndash;999) in not recognizing it taxonomically until more work is done.  \n\nThis comment applies to all the standard English names of the sea turtles listed herein.  We have returned to the use of &ldquo;sea turtles&rdquo; (rather than &ldquo;seaturtles&rdquo;) as part of the standard English name for marine turtles.  The combined name has not been used recently in the literature.', 'michelle koo', 'John B. Iverson (Chair), Peter A. Meylan, Michael E. Seidel', '', 0, 0, 0),
(16, 'chelydra', 'serpentina', '', 'snapping turtle', '', '', '', 'testudines', 'turtles', 'snapping turtles', '', 'testudines', 'schweigger', 'linnaeus', '{&quot;1812&quot;:&quot;1758&quot;}', '', 'This species has often been called the Common Snapping Turtle (e.g., Collins, 1997, SSAR Herpetol. Circ. 25).  We have dropped the adjective because it might be misinterpreted as referring to the abundance of the species rather than to its being the typical, most widespread species of its family.  Shaffer et al. (2008; Biology of the Snapping Turtle, John Hopkins Univ. Press.) provided convincing genetic evidence that *C. serpentina* is a &ldquo;single, virtually invariant lineage&rdquo; and hence abandoned the recognition of the subspecies *C. s. osceola* Stejneger, 1918.', 'michelle koo', 'John B. Iverson (Chair), Peter A. Meylan, Michael E. Seidel', '', 0, 0, 0),
