(70, 'macrochelys', 'appalachicolae', '', 'suwannee alligator snapping turtle', '', '', '', 'testudines', 'turtles', 'alligator snapping turtles', '', 'testudines', 'gray', 'thomas, granatosky, bourque, krysko, moler, gamble, suarez, leone, enge, and roman', '{&quot;1855&quot;:&quot;2014&quot;}', '', 'Note on genus:  \nWebb (1995, Chelonian Conserv. Biol. 1: 322&ndash;323) demonstrated that the name *Macrochelys* Gray has precedence over the name *Macroclemys* Gray (contra Smith, 1955, Herpetologica 11: 16). Preliminary mitochrondrial and microsatellite data (Roman et al., 1999, Conserv. Biol. 13: 135&ndash;142; Echelle et al., 2010, Conserv. Genetics 11: 1375&ndash;1387) had indicated the presence of significant genetic structure across the current range of this formerly monotypic genus.   Subsequently, Thomas et al. (2104, Zootaxa 3786(2): 1&ndash;165) provided further analysis of the mitochondrial data as well as morphological data that supported the recognition of three monophyletic lineages in this genus.  They retained the older species name for the western lineage, but those in the Apachicola and Suwannee River basins were described as full species.', 'michelle koo', 'John B. Iverson (Chair), Peter A. Meylan, Michael E. Seidel', '', 0, 0, 0),
(71, 'macrochelys', 'suwanniensis', '', 'apalachicola alligator snapping turtle', '', '', '', 'testudines', 'turtles', 'alligator snapping turtles', '', 'testudines', 'gray', 'thomas, granatosky, bourque, krysko, moler, gamble, suarez, leone, enge, and roman', '{&quot;1855&quot;:&quot;2014&quot;}', '', 'Note on genus:  \nWebb (1995, Chelonian Conserv. Biol. 1: 322&ndash;323) demonstrated that the name *Macrochelys* Gray has precedence over the name *Macroclemys* Gray (contra Smith, 1955, Herpetologica 11: 16). Preliminary mitochrondrial and microsatellite data (Roman et al., 1999, Conserv. Biol. 13: 135&ndash;142; Echelle et al., 2010, Conserv. Genetics 11: 1375&ndash;1387) had indicated the presence of significant genetic structure across the current range of this formerly monotypic genus.   Subsequently, Thomas et al. (2104, Zootaxa 3786(2): 1&ndash;165) provided further analysis of the mitochondrial data as well as morphological data that supported the recognition of three monophyletic lineages in this genus.  They retained the older species name for the western lineage, but those in the Apachicola and Suwannee River basins were described as full species.', 'michelle koo', 'John B. Iverson (Chair), Peter A. Meylan, Michael E. Seidel', '', 0, 0, 0),
(72, 'macrochelys', 'temminckii', '', 'alligator snapping turtle', '', '', '', 'testudines', 'turtles', 'alligator snapping turtles', '', 'testudines', 'gray', 'harlan', '{&quot;1855&quot;:&quot;1835&quot;}', '', 'Although Troost coined the species name, it was Harlan (1835) alone who authored the original description.  \n\nNote on genus:  \nWebb (1995, Chelonian Conserv. Biol. 1: 322&ndash;323) demonstrated that the name *Macrochelys* Gray has precedence over the name *Macroclemys* Gray (contra Smith, 1955, Herpetologica 11: 16). Preliminary mitochrondrial and microsatellite data (Roman et al., 1999, Conserv. Biol. 13: 135&ndash;142; Echelle et al., 2010, Conserv. Genetics 11: 1375&ndash;1387) had indicated the presence of significant genetic structure across the current range of this formerly monotypic genus.   Subsequently, Thomas et al. (2104, Zootaxa 3786(2): 1&ndash;165) provided further analysis of the mitochondrial data as well as morphological data that supported the recognition of three monophyletic lineages in this genus.  They retained the older species name for the western lineage, but those in the Apachicola and Suwannee River basins were described as full species.', 'michelle koo', 'John B. Iverson (Chair), Peter A. Meylan, Michael E. Seidel', '', 0, 0, 0),
