(150, 'coluber', 'bilineatus', '', 'sonoran whipsnake', '', '', '', 'squamata', 'snakes', 'north american racers, coachwhips and whipsnakes', '', 'serpentes', 'linnaeus', 'jan', '{&quot;1758&quot;:&quot;1863&quot;}', '{&quot;Masticophis bilineatus&quot;:&quot;Jan:1863&quot;}', 'Contrary to Collins (1997, SSAR Herpetol. Circ. 25: 1&ndash;40), Camper and Dixon (1994, Ann. Carnegie Mus. Nat. Hist. 63: 1&ndash;48) did not recognize any subspecies for *bilineatus*. Nagy et al. (2004, J. Zool. Syst. Evol. Res. 42: 223&ndash;233) restricted the genus *Coluber* to the new World and suggested that *Masticophis* might be paraphyletic with respect *Coluber*. Utiger et al. (2005, Russian J. Herpetol. 12: 39&ndash;60) corroborated Nagy et al., finding *Masticophis* to be paraphyletic with respect to *Coluber* and synonymizing *Masticophis* with *Coluber* (the oldest available name). This arrangement was also recovered in a recent phylogeny of Squamata (Pyron et al., 2013 BMC Evol. Biol. 13:93), albeit based on much of the same data.', 'carol spencer', 'Brian I. Crother (Chair), Jeff Boundy, Frank T. Burbrink, Jonathan A. Campbell, R. Alexander Pyron', '2014-12-12', 0, 1, 0),
(151, 'coluber', 'constrictor', '', 'north american racer', '', '', '', 'squamata', 'snakes', 'north american racers, coachwhips and whipsnakes', '', 'serpentes', 'linnaeus', 'linnaeus', '{&quot;1758&quot;:&quot;1758&quot;}', '', 'Nagy et al. (2004, J. Zool. Syst. Evol. Res. 42: 223&ndash;233) restricted the genus *Coluber* to the new World and suggested that *Masticophis* might be paraphyletic with respect *Coluber*. Utiger et al. (2005, Russian J. Herpetol. 12: 39&ndash;60) corroborated Nagy et al., finding *Masticophis* to be paraphyletic with respect to *Coluber* and synonymizing *Masticophis* with *Coluber* (the oldest available name). This arrangement was also recovered in a recent phylogeny of Squamata (Pyron et al., 2013 BMC Evol. Biol. 13:93), albeit based on much of the same data.Fitch et al. (1981, Trans, Kansas Acad. Sci. 84: 196&ndash;203) argued for the elevation of *C. c. mormon.* This recommendation was rejected by Greene (1983, J. Herpetol. 18: 210&ndash;211), and was supported by Corn and Bury (1986, Herpetologica 42: 258&ndash;264), who showed a broad zone of intergradation across Colorado and Utah. Collins (1991, Herpetol. Rev. 22: 42&ndash;43) re-elevated mormon to specific status, although allopatry was not suitably demonstrated. Anderson (1996, MS thesis, Southeastern Louisiana Univ.) argued that based on allozyme data *C. c. mormon* cannot be differentiated but that *C. c. paludicola* and *C. c. oaxaca* were diagnosable and should be elevated to species status. We retain *C. c. mormon* and await action on *oaxaca* and *paludicola* until the data are published. Burbrink et al. (2008, Mol. Phylogen. Evol 47: 274&ndash;288) have demonstrated using mtDNA that *C. constrictor* may be composed of six independently evolving lineages not concordant with most recognized subspecies. In particular, neither *C. c. mormon* or *C. paludicola* represents an evolutionarily distinct lineage. No samples of *C. c. oaxaca* were included.', 'carol spencer', 'Brian I. Crother (Chair), Jeff Boundy, Frank T. Burbrink, Jonathan A. Campbell, R. Alexander Pyron', '2014-12-12', 0, 0, 0),
