(182, 'contia', 'longicauda', '', 'forest sharp-tailed snake', '', '', '', 'squamata', 'snakes', 'sharp-tailed snakes', '', 'serpentes', 'baird and girard', 'feldman and hoyer', '{&quot;1853&quot;:&quot;2010&quot;}', '', 'This  species  was  originally  named *Contia  longicaudae*  by  Feldman  and  Hoyer  (2010,  Copeia,  2010:  254&ndash;267); however, because they explicitly treated the second part of the binomen as an adjective, it must agree with the name *Contia* in gender and number so that the correct spelling is *Contia longicauda*.', 'carol spencer', 'Brian I. Crother (Chair), Jeff Boundy, Frank T. Burbrink, Jonathan A. Campbell, R. Alexander Pyron', '2014-12-12', 0, 0, 0),
(183, 'contia', 'tenuis', '', 'common sharp-tailed snake', '', '', '', 'squamata', 'snakes', 'sharp-tailed snakes', '', 'serpentes', 'baird and girard', 'baird and girard', '{&quot;1853&quot;:&quot;1852&quot;}', '', '', 'carol spencer', 'Brian I. Crother (Chair), Jeff Boundy, Frank T. Burbrink, Jonathan A. Campbell, R. Alexander Pyron', '2014-12-12', 0, 1, 0),
(184, 'crotalus', 'adamanteus', '', 'eastern diamond-backed rattlesnake', '', '', '', 'squamata', 'snakes', 'rattlesnakes', '', 'serpentes', 'linnaeus', 'palisot de beauvois', '{&quot;1758&quot;:&quot;1799&quot;}', '', 'Notes on the Genus: \nThe traditional view of rattlesnake taxonomy that recognizes the two monophyletic sister genera *Crotalus* and *Sistrurus* (e.g, Brattstrom, 1964, San Diego Soc. Nat. Hist. 13: 185&ndash;268) has recently been challenged. Stille (1987, Herpetologica 43: 98&ndash;104) and McCranie (1989, Herpetologica 44: 123&ndash;126) presented data that suggested *Sistrurus* is not monophyletic and rendered *Crotalus* paraphyletic. Parkinson (1999, Copeia 1999: 576&ndash;586) found *Sistrurus* monophyletic but its position rendered *Crotalus* paraphyletic. Knight et al. (1993, Syst. Biol. 42: 356&ndash;367) used mtDNA to defend the traditional generic taxonomy, but in order to do so ignored the most parsimonious tree. The genus *Crotalus* is monophyletic when including the Mexican *C. ravus* (Murphy et al. 2002, in Schuett et al., [eds.] Biology of the Vipers, Eagle Mountain Publishing, Pp. 69&ndash;92), and is supported as such in most recent phylogenies, as well as being the sister taxon to a monophyletic *Sistrurus* (e.g., Pyron et al., 2013; BMC Evol. Biol. 13: 93).', 'carol spencer', 'Brian I. Crother (Chair), Jeff Boundy, Frank T. Burbrink, Jonathan A. Campbell, R. Alexander Pyron', '2014-12-12', 0, 0, 0),
(185, 'crotalus', 'atrox', '', 'western diamond-backed rattlesnake', '', '', '', 'squamata', 'snakes', 'rattlesnakes', '', 'serpentes', 'linnaeus', 'baird and girard', '{&quot;1758&quot;:&quot;1853&quot;}', '', 'Notes on the Genus: \nThe traditional view of rattlesnake taxonomy that recognizes the two monophyletic sister genera *Crotalus* and *Sistrurus* (e.g, Brattstrom, 1964, San Diego Soc. Nat. Hist. 13: 185&ndash;268) has recently been challenged. Stille (1987, Herpetologica 43: 98&ndash;104) and McCranie (1989, Herpetologica 44: 123&ndash;126) presented data that suggested *Sistrurus* is not monophyletic and rendered *Crotalus* paraphyletic. Parkinson (1999, Copeia 1999: 576&ndash;586) found *Sistrurus* monophyletic but its position rendered *Crotalus* paraphyletic. Knight et al. (1993, Syst. Biol. 42: 356&ndash;367) used mtDNA to defend the traditional generic taxonomy, but in order to do so ignored the most parsimonious tree. The genus *Crotalus* is monophyletic when including the Mexican *C. ravus* (Murphy et al. 2002, in Schuett et al., [eds.] Biology of the Vipers, Eagle Mountain Publishing, Pp. 69&ndash;92), and is supported as such in most recent phylogenies, as well as being the sister taxon to a monophyletic *Sistrurus* (e.g., Pyron et al., 2013; BMC Evol. Biol. 13: 93).', 'carol spencer', 'Brian I. Crother (Chair), Jeff Boundy, Frank T. Burbrink, Jonathan A. Campbell, R. Alexander Pyron', '2014-12-12', 0, 0, 0),
(186, 'crotalus', 'cerastes', '', 'sidewinder', 'species&#95;photos/Crotalus&#95;cerastes&#95;mesquite&#95;springs&#95;CA-2.jpg', 'Philip Kahn', 'CC BY-SA 3.0', 'squamata', 'snakes', 'rattlesnakes', '', 'serpentes', 'linnaeus', 'hallowell', '{&quot;1758&quot;:&quot;1854&quot;}', '', 'Douglas et al. (2006, Mol. Ecol. 15: 3353&ndash;3374), using mtDNA, found several geographically distinct lineages within *C. cerastes*.  Only one of these lineages corresponded to a recognized subspecies. (*C. c. laterorepens*).\nNotes on the Genus: \nThe traditional view of rattlesnake taxonomy that recognizes the two monophyletic sister genera *Crotalus* and *Sistrurus* (e.g, Brattstrom, 1964, San Diego Soc. Nat. Hist. 13: 185&ndash;268) has recently been challenged. Stille (1987, Herpetologica 43: 98&ndash;104) and McCranie (1989, Herpetologica 44: 123&ndash;126) presented data that suggested *Sistrurus* is not monophyletic and rendered *Crotalus* paraphyletic. Parkinson (1999, Copeia 1999: 576&ndash;586) found *Sistrurus* monophyletic but its position rendered *Crotalus* paraphyletic. Knight et al. (1993, Syst. Biol. 42: 356&ndash;367) used mtDNA to defend the traditional generic taxonomy, but in order to do so ignored the most parsimonious tree. The genus *Crotalus* is monophyletic when including the Mexican *C. ravus* (Murphy et al. 2002, in Schuett et al., [eds.] Biology of the Vipers, Eagle Mountain Publishing, Pp. 69&ndash;92), and is supported as such in most recent phylogenies, as well as being the sister taxon to a monophyletic *Sistrurus* (e.g., Pyron et al., 2013; BMC Evol. Biol. 13: 93).', 'carol spencer', 'Brian I. Crother (Chair), Jeff Boundy, Frank T. Burbrink, Jonathan A. Campbell, R. Alexander Pyron', '2014-12-12', 0, 0, 0),
