(236, 'ficimia', 'streckeri', '', 'tamaulipan hook-nosed snake', '', '', '', 'squamata', 'snakes', 'eastern hook-nosed snakes', '', 'serpentes', 'gray', 'taylor', '{&quot;1849&quot;:&quot;1931&quot;}', '', 'The previous Standard English names of *Ficimia* and *Gyalopion* were misleading relative to their geographic ranges. All are distributed in Mexico, but *Ficimia* had the moniker &ldquo;Mexican,&rdquo; whereas *Gyalopion* had the name &ldquo;Plateau,&rdquo; yet is clearly not confined to any plateau.  Given that *Ficimia* has the easternmost distribution, we call it &ldquo;Eastern&rdquo; and call *Gyalopion* &ldquo;Western.&rdquo;', 'carol spencer', 'Brian I. Crother (Chair), Jeff Boundy, Frank T. Burbrink, Jonathan A. Campbell, R. Alexander Pyron', '2014-12-12', 0, 0, 0),
(237, 'gyalopion', 'canum', '', 'chihuahuan hook-nosed snake', '', '', '', 'squamata', 'snakes', 'western hook-nosed snakes', '', 'serpentes', 'cope', 'cope', '{&quot;1861&quot;:&quot;1861 \\&quot;1860\\&quot;&quot;}', '', 'The previous Standard English names of *Ficimia* and *Gyalopion* were misleading relative to their geographic ranges. All are distributed in Mexico, but *Ficimia* had the moniker &ldquo;Mexican,&rdquo; whereas *Gyalopion* had the name &ldquo;Plateau,&rdquo; yet is clearly not confined to any plateau.  Given that *Ficimia* has the easternmost distribution, we call it &ldquo;Eastern&rdquo; and call *Gyalopion* &ldquo;Western.&rdquo;', 'carol spencer', 'Brian I. Crother (Chair), Jeff Boundy, Frank T. Burbrink, Jonathan A. Campbell, R. Alexander Pyron', '2014-12-12', 0, 0, 0),
(238, 'gyalopion', 'quadrangulare', '', 'thornscrub hook-nosed snake', '', '', '', 'squamata', 'snakes', 'western hook-nosed snakes', '', 'serpentes', 'cope', 'g&uuml;nther in salvin and godman, 1885-1902', '{&quot;1861&quot;:&quot;1893&quot;}', '', 'The previous Standard English names of *Ficimia* and *Gyalopion* were misleading relative to their geographic ranges. All are distributed in Mexico, but *Ficimia* had the moniker &ldquo;Mexican,&rdquo; whereas *Gyalopion* had the name &ldquo;Plateau,&rdquo; yet is clearly not confined to any plateau.  Given that *Ficimia* has the easternmost distribution, we call it &ldquo;Eastern&rdquo; and call *Gyalopion* &ldquo;Western.&rdquo;', 'carol spencer', 'Brian I. Crother (Chair), Jeff Boundy, Frank T. Burbrink, Jonathan A. Campbell, R. Alexander Pyron', '2014-12-12', 0, 1, 0),
(239, 'haldea', 'striatula', '', 'rough earthsnake', '', '', '', 'squamata', 'snakes', 'rough earthsnakes', '', 'serpentes', 'baird and girard', 'linnaeus', '{&quot;1853&quot;:&quot;1766&quot;}', '', 'McVay and Carstens (2013, Mol. Phylogenet. Evol. 68: 425&ndash;431) found that *Virginia* is polyphyletic based on a multi-locus nuclear dataset, and resurrected *Haldea* for *V. striatula*.', 'carol spencer', 'Brian I. Crother (Chair), Jeff Boundy, Frank T. Burbrink, Jonathan A. Campbell, R. Alexander Pyron', '2014-12-12', 0, 1, 0),
(240, 'heterodon', 'gloydi', '', 'dusty hog-nosed snake', '', '', '', 'squamata', 'snakes', 'north american hog-nosed snakes', '', 'serpentes', 'latreille', 'edgren', '{&quot;1801&quot;:&quot;1952&quot;}', '', 'Werler and Dixon (2000, Texas Snakes, University of Texas Press, Austin) regarded *H. n. gloydi* to be an allopatric, diagnosable taxon restricted to the low plains - eastern forest ecotone of eastern Texas. Smith et al. (2003, J. Kansas Herpetol. 5: 17&ndash;20) countered that it was not diagnosable.', 'carol spencer', 'Brian I. Crother (Chair), Jeff Boundy, Frank T. Burbrink, Jonathan A. Campbell, R. Alexander Pyron', '2014-12-12', 0, 0, 0),
(241, 'heterodon', 'kennerlyi', '', 'mexican hog-nosed snake', '', '', '', 'squamata', 'snakes', 'north american hog-nosed snakes', '', 'serpentes', 'latreille', 'kennicott', '{&quot;1801&quot;:&quot;1860&quot;}', '', 'Smith et al. (2003, J. Kansas Herpetol. 5: 17&ndash;20), based on two scale characters, separated *H. n. kennerlyi* from *H. n. nasicus* and elevated the former to species.', 'carol spencer', 'Brian I. Crother (Chair), Jeff Boundy, Frank T. Burbrink, Jonathan A. Campbell, R. Alexander Pyron', '2014-12-12', 0, 0, 0),
(242, 'heterodon', 'nasicus', '', 'plains hog-nosed snake', '', '', '', 'squamata', 'snakes', 'north american hog-nosed snakes', '', 'serpentes', 'latreille', 'baird and girard', '{&quot;1801&quot;:&quot;1852&quot;}', '', 'Because the three subspecies of *H. nasicus* have been elevated to species, their respective standard English names remain associated with each. Hence, there is no longer a &ldquo;Western Hog-nosed Snake.&rdquo;', 'carol spencer', 'Brian I. Crother (Chair), Jeff Boundy, Frank T. Burbrink, Jonathan A. Campbell, R. Alexander Pyron', '2014-12-12', 0, 0, 0),
(243, 'heterodon', 'platirhinos', '', 'eastern hog-nosed snake', '', '', '', 'squamata', 'snakes', 'north american hog-nosed snakes', '', 'serpentes', 'latreille', 'latreille', '{&quot;1801&quot;:&quot;1801&quot;}', '', '', 'carol spencer', 'Brian I. Crother (Chair), Jeff Boundy, Frank T. Burbrink, Jonathan A. Campbell, R. Alexander Pyron', '2014-12-12', 0, 0, 0),
(244, 'heterodon', 'simus', '', 'southern hog-nosed snake', '', '', '', 'squamata', 'snakes', 'north american hog-nosed snakes', '', 'serpentes', 'latreille', 'linnaeus', '{&quot;1801&quot;:&quot;1766&quot;}', '', '', 'carol spencer', 'Brian I. Crother (Chair), Jeff Boundy, Frank T. Burbrink, Jonathan A. Campbell, R. Alexander Pyron', '2014-12-12', 0, 1, 0),
(245, 'hydrophis', 'platurus', '', 'yellow-bellied snake', '', '', '', 'squamata', 'snakes', 'seasnakes', '', 'serpentes', 'latreille *ex* sonnini and latreille', 'linnaeus', '{&quot;1801&quot;:&quot;1766&quot;}', '', 'A recent study (Sanders et al., 2013, Mol. Phylogenet. Evol. 66: 575&ndash;591) corrected the long-noted non-monophyly of most sea snake genera (including *Pelamis*) by recognizing a single large genus *Hydrophis*, including *H. platurus*.', 'carol spencer', 'Brian I. Crother (Chair), Jeff Boundy, Frank T. Burbrink, Jonathan A. Campbell, R. Alexander Pyron', '2014-12-12', 0, 1, 0),
(246, 'hypsiglena', 'chlorophaea', '', 'desert nightsnake', '', '', '', 'squamata', 'snakes', 'north american nightsnakes', '', 'serpentes', 'cope', 'cope', '{&quot;1860&quot;:&quot;1860&quot;}', '', 'Taxonomy of *Hypsiglena* has received some critical review since Tanner&#39;s revision of the genus (1944, Great Basin Nat. 5: 25&ndash;92). Dixon (1965, Southwest. Nat. 10: 125&ndash;131) and Dixon and Dean (1986, Southwest. Nat. 31: 307&ndash;318) studied a morphological contact zone between northern and southern taxa at the Sonora&not;&ndash;Sinaloa border in Mexico, finding that it comprised a narrow zone of hybridization with some taxa existing in sympatry. Hardy and McDiarmid (1969, Univ. Kansas Pub. Mus. Nat. Hist. 18: 39&ndash;252) examined specimens across the range of this presumptive contact and elsewhere in western Mexico and concluded that no morphological characters existed to separate *torquata* and *ochrorhyncha*, except maybe nuchal patterns, which they decided (p. 170) was &quot;a case of pattern dimorphism in a single, otherwise uniform, species.&quot; Grismer et al. (1994, Bull. So. California Acad. Sci. 93: 45&ndash;80) dismissed the recognition of subspecies in Baja California, stating, without evidence, that the subspecies intergrade widely. Mulcahy (2008,Mol. Phylogenet. Evol. 46: 1095&ndash;1115) conducted a comprehensive phylogeographic study of *Hypsiglena* based on an mtDNA analysis of  &gt;150 individuals. Mulcahy (2008) recognized six species in what was considered *H. torquata*, five of which are consistent with previously described lineages (e.g., subspecies), while one represents a unique lineage that remains to be described.  Mulcahy (2008) also recommended maintaining the subspecies designations for several of the widespread, polymorphic species, which may represent incipient species. The nominal species *H. torquata* is now restricted to Mexico, three described forms occur in the USA, and the undescribed form is endemic to the Cochise Filter Barrier area of southeastern Arizona and associated New Mexico.', 'carol spencer', 'Brian I. Crother (Chair), Jeff Boundy, Frank T. Burbrink, Jonathan A. Campbell, R. Alexander Pyron', '2014-12-12', 0, 0, 0),
