(316, 'pantherophis', 'alleghaniensis', '', 'eastern ratsnake', '', '', '', 'squamata', 'snakes', 'north american ratsnakes', '', 'serpentes', 'fitzinger', 'holbrook', '{&quot;1843&quot;:&quot;1836&quot;}', '', 'Based on the congruence of morphological (Burbrink, 2001, Herpetol. Monogr. 15: 1&ndash;53) and mitochondrial data (Burbrink et al., 2000, Evolution 54: 2107&ndash;2118), Burbrink divided *P. obsoletus* into three species (*P. alleghaniensis, P. obsoletus* and *P. spiloides*) with no subspecies.', 'michelle koo', 'Brian I. Crother (Chair), Jeff Boundy, Frank T. Burbrink, Jonathan A. Campbell, R. Alexander Pyron', '2014-12-12', 0, 1, 0),
(317, 'pantherophis', 'bairdi', '', 'baird&amp;#39;s ratsnake', '', '', '', 'squamata', 'snakes', 'north american ratsnakes', '', 'serpentes', 'fitzinger', 'yarrow, in cope', '{&quot;1843&quot;:&quot;1880&quot;}', '', '', 'michelle koo', '', '', 0, 1, 0),
(318, 'pantherophis', 'emoryi', '', 'great plains ratsnake', '', '', '', 'squamata', 'snakes', 'north american ratsnakes', '', 'serpentes', 'fitzinger', 'baird and girard', '{&quot;1843&quot;:&quot;1853&quot;}', '', 'Using mitochondrial data, Burbrink (2002, Mol. Phylogenet. Evol. 25: 465&ndash;476) found *P. guttatus* to comprise three distinct lineages, which were elevated to species level. The name *P. guttatus* was restricted to populations east of the Mississippi River. The populations in western Louisiana and eastern Texas were named *P. slowinskii.*\nThe subspecies *P. g. meahllmorum* was not found to be a distinct lineage, and was synonymized with *P. emoryi*.', 'michelle koo', 'Brian I. Crother (Chair), Jeff Boundy, Frank T. Burbrink, Jonathan A. Campbell, R. Alexander Pyron', '2014-12-12', 0, 1, 0),
(319, 'pantherophis', 'guttatus', '', 'red cornsnake', '', '', '', 'squamata', 'snakes', 'north american ratsnakes', '', 'serpentes', 'fitzinger', 'linnaeus', '{&quot;1843&quot;:&quot;1766&quot;}', '', 'Using mitochondrial data, Burbrink (2002, Mol. Phylogenet. Evol. 25: 465&ndash;476) found *P. guttatus* to comprise three distinct lineages, which were elevated to species level. The name *P. guttatus* was restricted to populations east of the Mississippi River. The populations in western Louisiana and eastern Texas were named *P. slowinskii.*\nThe subspecies *P. g. meahllmorum* was not found to be a distinct lineage, and was synonymized with *P. emoryi*.', 'michelle koo', 'Brian I. Crother (Chair), Jeff Boundy, Frank T. Burbrink, Jonathan A. Campbell, R. Alexander Pyron', '2014-12-12', 0, 1, 0),
(320, 'pantherophis', 'obsoletus', '', 'western ratsnake', '', '', '', 'squamata', 'snakes', 'north american ratsnakes', '', 'serpentes', 'fitzinger', 'say', '{&quot;1843&quot;:&quot;1823&quot;}', '', 'Based on the congruence of morphological (Burbrink, 2001, Herpetol. Monogr. 15: 1&ndash;53) and mitochondrial data (Burbrink et al., 2000, Evolution 54: 2107&ndash;2118), Burbrink divided *P. obsoletus* into three species (*P. alleghaniensis, P. obsoletus* and *P. spiloides*) with no subspecies.', 'michelle koo', 'Brian I. Crother (Chair), Jeff Boundy, Frank T. Burbrink, Jonathan A. Campbell, R. Alexander Pyron', '2014-12-12', 0, 1, 0),
(321, 'pantherophis', 'ramspotti', '', 'western foxsnake', '', '', '', 'squamata', 'snakes', 'north american ratsnakes', '', 'serpentes', 'fitzinger', 'crother, white, savage, eckstut, graham, and gardner', '{&quot;1843&quot;:&quot;2011&quot;}', '', 'Conant (1940, Herpetologica 2: 2) recognized two forms of foxsnakes, one on each side of a geographic disjunction (basically all of Michigan and parts of Indiana and Ohio) with the western form as *Pantherophis vulpinus vulpinus* and the eastern form as *P. v. gloydi*. Collins (1991, Herpetol. Rev. 22: 42&ndash;43) elevated *gloydi* to specific status because of its geographic disjunction from *vulpinus* and the characters noted by Conant (1940, Herpetologica 2: 2). Crother et al. (2011, ISRN Zoology, doi:10.5402/2011/436049) supported the concept of two species, but discovered that the species boundary was the Mississippi River and not the disjunction. The type locality of *P. vulpinus* is east of the Mississippi River and thus the appropriate available name for the eastern form, leaving the western form unnamed. An interesting side note is that faster evolving microsatellite data reveal a population level separation associated with the geographic hiatus (Row et al., 2011, J Evol. Biol. 24: 2364&ndash;2377).', 'michelle koo', 'Brian I. Crother (Chair), Jeff Boundy, Frank T. Burbrink, Jonathan A. Campbell, R. Alexander Pyron', '2014-12-12', 0, 0, 0),
