(571, 'gyrinophilus', 'gulolineatus', '', 'berry cave salamander ', '', '', '', 'caudata', 'salamanders', 'spring salamander', '', 'caudata', 'cope', 'brandon', '{&quot;1869&quot;:&quot;1965&quot;}', '', 'Niemiller, et al. (2008, Molec. Ecol. 17: 2258&ndash;2275) provide molecular evidence indicating that this form has diverged very recently from *G. porphyriticus* and is phylogenetically nested within populations referred to that species.  Niemiller and Miller (2010, Cat. of American Amph. and Rept. 862: 1&ndash;4), Miller and Niemiller (2012, Cat. of American Amph. And Rept. 884: 1&ndash;7), and Raffa&euml;lli (2013, Les Urod&egrave;les du Monde, 2e  edition, Penclen &Eacute;dition, France &ndash; no city given) treat the taxon as a full species, while Fouquette and Dubois (2014, A Checklist of North American Amphibians and Reptiles, The United States and Canada, Seventh Edition, Vol. 1 &ndash; Amphibians, Xlibris, San Bernardino, CA, 613 p.) treat it as a subspecies of *G. &ldquo;porphoriticus&rdquo;*. Bonnet, et al. (2013 [2014], Evolution 68: 466-482) treat it as a subspecies of G. palleucus in their trees but refer to it as a full species in their text. While closely related to G. palleucus, the taxon is distinguished from it in body proportions, osteology, colorations and some genetical aspects (Niemiller and Miller, 2010).', 'michelle koo', 'Stephen G. Tilley (Chair), Richard Highton, David B. Wake', '', 0, 0, 0),
(572, 'gyrinophilus', 'palleucus', '', 'tennessee cave salamander', '', '', '', 'caudata', 'salamanders', 'spring salamander', '', 'caudata', 'cope', 'mccrady', '{&quot;1869&quot;:&quot;1954&quot;}', '', 'Fouquette and Dubois (2014, A Checklist of North American Amphibians and Reptiles, The United States and Canada, Seventh Edition, Vol. 1 &ndash; Amphibians, Xlibris, San Bernardino, CA, 613 p.) treat this taxon and its subspecies as subspecies of *G. porphyriticus*, citing a close relationship to a population of that species suggested in trees in Bonnet, et al. (2013 [2014], Evolution 68: 466-482).  That relationship lacks strong statistical support and the latter authors drew no taxonomic conclusions. ', 'michelle koo', 'Stephen G. Tilley (Chair), Richard Highton, David B. Wake', '', 0, 0, 0),
