(736, 'hyla', 'wrightorum', '', 'arizona treefrog', '', '', '', 'anura', 'frogs', 'holarctic treefrogs', '', 'anura', 'laurenti', 'taylor', '{&quot;1768&quot;:&quot;1939 \\&quot;1938\\&quot;&quot;}', '', 'Gergus et al. (2004, Copeia 2004: 758&ndash;769) reported on the distinctiveness of this species with respect to *H. eximia* (extralimital). See comment under *H. arenicolor*. Reviewed by Gergus, Wallace, and Sullivan (2005, in Lannoo, M. [ed.], Amph. Declines: 461&ndash;463) and Dodd (2013, Frogs U.S. and Canada, 1: 309&ndash;332).', 'michelle koo', 'Darrel R. Frost, David M. Green, Emily Moriarty Lemmon, Roy W. McDiarmid, and Joseph R. Mendelson III', '', 0, 0, 0),
(737, 'hypopachus', 'variolosus', '', 'sheep frog', '', '', '', 'anura', 'frogs', 'sheep frogs', '', 'anura', 'keferstein', 'cope', '{&quot;1867&quot;:&quot;1866&quot;}', '', 'See Nelson (1973, Herpetologica 29: 6&ndash;17; 1974, Herpetologica 30: 250&ndash;274) for discussion of geographic variation and rejection of subspecies. USA population reviewed by Judd and Irwin (2005, in Lannoo, M. [ed.], Amph. Declines: 506&ndash;508) and Dodd (2013, Frogs U.S. and Canada, 1: 455&ndash;457). Although only two species are currently recognized within this genus, very strong geographic variation in coloration, call, and toe structure suggests that several species are masquerading under this particular name. Given that the type locality of *H. variolosus* is in Costa Rica, the scientific name applied to the U.S. form is likely to change.', 'michelle koo', 'Darrel R. Frost, David M. Green, Emily Moriarty Lemmon, Roy W. McDiarmid, and Joseph R. Mendelson III', '', 0, 0, 0),
(738, 'incilius', 'alvarius', '', 'sonoran desert toad', '', '', '', 'anura', 'frogs', 'central american toads', '', 'anura', 'cope', 'girard', '{&quot;1863&quot;:&quot;1859&quot;}', '', 'Reviewed by Fouquette (1970, Cat. Am. Amph. Rept. 93, as *Bufo alvarius*), Fouquette, Painter, and Nanjappa, (2005, in Lannoo, M. [ed.], Amph. Declines: 384&ndash;386, as *Bufo alvarius*), and Dodd (2013, Frogs U.S. and Canada, 1: 177&ndash;180).  \n\nNote on genus:  \nThis taxon of predominantly Central American toads was removed from a paraphyletic &ldquo;*Bufo*&rdquo; by Frost et al. (2006, Bull. Am. Mus. Nat. Hist., 297; as *Cranopsis*). However, the oldest name for this taxon is *Incilius* Cope, 1863 (see Frost et al., 2009, Copeia 2009: 418&ndash;419) which therefore takes precedence. See comment under *Anaxyrus*. Van Bocxlaer et al. (2010, Science, 327: 679&ndash;682) presented evidence that *Incilius* may be paraphyletic with respect to *Anaxyrus* due to the placement of one extralimital species, although this was based on a small dataset (Mendelson et al., 2011, Zootaxa, 3138: 1-34). See comment under *Anaxyrus*, regarding the treatment of this genus as a subgenus of *Bufo* by some although the effect extralimitally of subgeneric status would be to require a number well-marked genera (e.g., *Ansonia*) to be treated as subgenera as well.', 'michelle koo', 'Darrel R. Frost, David M. Green, Emily Moriarty Lemmon, Roy W. McDiarmid, and Joseph R. Mendelson III', '', 0, 0, 0),
(739, 'incilius', 'nebulifer', '', 'gulf coast toad', '', '', '', 'anura', 'frogs', 'central american toads', '', 'anura', 'cope', 'girard', '{&quot;1863&quot;:&quot;1854&quot;}', '', 'Mulcahy and Mendelson (2000, Mol. Phylogenet. Evol. 17: 173) recognized this species, as *Bufo nebulifer*, and as distinct from *I. valliceps*, an extralimital species. Reviewed by Mendelson (2005, in Lannoo, M. [ed.], Amph. Declines: 424&ndash;427, as *Bufo nebulifer*) and Dodd (2013, Frogs U.S. and Canada, 1: 180&ndash;186).   \n\n\nNote on genus:  \nThis taxon of predominantly Central American toads was removed from a paraphyletic &ldquo;*Bufo*&rdquo; by Frost et al. (2006, Bull. Am. Mus. Nat. Hist., 297; as *Cranopsis*). However, the oldest name for this taxon is *Incilius* Cope, 1863 (see Frost et al., 2009, Copeia 2009: 418&ndash;419) which therefore takes precedence. See comment under *Anaxyrus*. Van Bocxlaer et al. (2010, Science, 327: 679&ndash;682) presented evidence that *Incilius* may be paraphyletic with respect to *Anaxyrus* due to the placement of one extralimital species, although this was based on a small dataset (Mendelson et al., 2011, Zootaxa, 3138: 1-34). See comment under *Anaxyrus*, regarding the treatment of this genus as a subgenus of *Bufo* by some although the effect extralimitally of subgeneric status would be to require a number well-marked genera (e.g., *Ansonia*) to be treated as subgenera as well.', 'michelle koo', 'Darrel R. Frost, David M. Green, Emily Moriarty Lemmon, Roy W. McDiarmid, and Joseph R. Mendelson III', '', 0, 0, 0),
(740, 'leptodactylus', 'fragilis', '', 'mexican white-lipped frogs', '', '', '', 'anura', 'frogs', 'neotropical grass frogs', '', 'anura', 'fitzinger', 'brocchi', '{&quot;1826&quot;:&quot;1877&quot;}', '', 'Reviewed by Heyer et al. (2006, Cat. Am. Amph. Rept. 830), Heyer (2005, in Lannoo, M. [ed.], Amph. Declines: 500&ndash;501),  Dodd, 2013, Frogs U.S. and Canada, 1: 436&ndash;438. Much of the older literature about this species refers to it incorrectly as *Leptodactylus labialis*.', 'michelle koo', 'Darrel R. Frost, David M. Green, Emily Moriarty Lemmon, Roy W. McDiarmid, and Joseph R. Mendelson III', '', 0, 0, 0),
(741, 'lithobates', 'areolatus', '', 'crawfish frog', '', '', '', 'anura', 'frogs', 'american water frogs', '', 'anura', 'fitzinger', 'baird and girard', '{&quot;1843&quot;:&quot;1852&quot;}', '', 'See comment under *L. capito*. Reviewed by Altig and Lohoefener (1983, Cat. Am. Amph. Rept. 324, as *Rana areolata*), Parris and Redmer (2005,in Lannoo, M. [ed.], Amph. Declines: 526&ndash;528), and Dodd (2013, Frogs U.S. and Canada, 2 : 461&ndash;466). Geographic variation deserves further study to determine status of the nominal subspecies.  \n\nNotes on genus:  \nThis taxon of North, Central, and South American frogs was removed from the large and predominantly Eurasian genus *Rana* by Frost et al. (2006, Bull. Am. Mus. Nat. Hist., 297). Hillis and Wilcox (2005, Mol. Phylogenet. Evol. 34: 299&ndash;314) provided a phylogenetic taxonomy that retained the species now under *Lithobates* within *Rana* and restricted the use of that name to a small part of what was subsequently assigned to *Lithobates* by Frost et al. (2006). Dubois (2006, Mol. Phylogenet. Evol. 42: 317&ndash;330) criticized the nomenclatural proposals of Hillis and Wilcox and regarded their names as *nomina nuda* and their approach outside of the International Code of Zoological Nomenclature (1999). This criticism was responded to by Hillis (2006, Mol. Phylogenet. Evol. 42: 331&ndash;338), who argued that most of the new names proposed by Hillis and Wilcox do have nomenclatural status under the International Code of Zoological Nomenclature (1999). The revision by Che et al. (2007, Mol. Phylogenet. Evol. 42: 1&ndash;13) which recognized *Lithobates* as a genus, we think best reflects the majority opinion of members of the international community who are actively working on large-scale ranid relationships, although Hillis, 2007 (Mol. Phylogenet. Evol. 42: 331-338) and Wiens et al. (2009, Evolution 63: 1217&ndash;1231) expressed reluctance to accept this taxonomy. Dubois (2006, Mol. Phylogenet. Evol. 42: 317&