(775, 'pseudacris', 'kalmi', '', 'new jersey chorus frog', '', '', '', 'anura', 'frogs', 'chorus frogs', '', 'anura', 'fitzinger', 'harper', '{&quot;1843&quot;:&quot;1955&quot;}', '', 'Platz (1989, Copeia 1989: 704&ndash;712) retained *P. feriarum* and *P. kalmi* as subspecies of one species but suggested that they might also be distinct species on the basis of data presented by Hedges (1986, Syst. Zool. 35: 1&ndash;21). Lemmon et al. (2007, Mol. Phylogenet. Evol. 44: 1068&ndash;1082) confirmed that *P. kalmi* and *P. feriarum* are distinct species although the contact zone between these taxa is poorly understood.  \n\nNote on genus:  \nLemmon et al. (2007, Mol. Phylogenet. Evol. 44: 1068&ndash;1082) revised the *P. nigrita* group (*P. brimleyi, P. brachyphona, P. clarkii, P. feriarum, P. kalmi, P. maculata*, and *P. triseriata* and an unnamed species, which was subsequently named as *Pseudacris fouquettei*). Fouquette and Dubois (2014, Checklist N.A. Amph. Rept.) deployed a system of subgenera based on the work of Lemmon et al., placing the eastern species in the subgenus *Pseudacris* and the western members (*P. cadaverina, P. hypchondriaca, P. regilla*, and *P. sierra*) in the subgenus *Hyliola*, and the species *P. ocularis* and *P. crucifer* in the subgenus *Limnaoedus* but we have not adopted subgenera in this list.', 'michelle koo', 'Darrel R. Frost, David M. Green, Emily Moriarty Lemmon, Roy W. McDiarmid, and Joseph R. Mendelson III', '', 0, 0, 0),
(776, 'pseudacris', 'maculata', '', 'boreal chorus frog', '', '', '', 'anura', 'frogs', 'chorus frogs', '', 'anura', 'fitzinger', 'agassiz', '{&quot;1843&quot;:&quot;1850&quot;}', '', 'Considered a species distinct from *P. triseriata* by Platz (1989, Copeia 1989: 704&ndash;712). Lemmon et al. (2007, Mol. Phylogenet. Evol. 44: 1068&ndash;1082) revised the geographic limits of this species although the evidence based only on mitochondrial DNA variation was not accepted by Green et al. (2013, N.A. Amphibians). Reviewed by Dodd (2013, Frogs U.S. and Canada, 1: 371&ndash;384). \n\nNote on genus:  \nLemmon et al. (2007, Mol. Phylogenet. Evol. 44: 1068&ndash;1082) revised the *P. nigrita* group (*P. brimleyi, P. brachyphona, P. clarkii, P. feriarum, P. kalmi, P. maculata*, and *P. triseriata* and an unnamed species, which was subsequently named as *Pseudacris fouquettei*). Fouquette and Dubois (2014, Checklist N.A. Amph. Rept.) deployed a system of subgenera based on the work of Lemmon et al., placing the eastern species in the subgenus *Pseudacris* and the western members (*P. cadaverina, P. hypchondriaca, P. regilla*, and *P. sierra*) in the subgenus *Hyliola*, and the species *P. ocularis* and *P. crucifer* in the subgenus *Limnaoedus* but we have not adopted subgenera in this list.', 'michelle koo', 'Darrel R. Frost, David M. Green, Emily Moriarty Lemmon, Roy W. McDiarmid, and Joseph R. Mendelson III', '', 0, 0, 0),
(777, 'pseudacris', 'nigrita', '', 'southern chorus frog', '', '', '', 'anura', 'frogs', 'chorus frogs', '', 'anura', 'fitzinger', 'leconte', '{&quot;1843&quot;:&quot;1825&quot;}', '', 'Reviewed by Gates (1988, Cat. Am. Amph. Rept. 416), Leja (2005, in Lannoo, M. [ed.], Amph. Declines: 474&ndash;475), and Dodd ( 2013, Frogs U.S. and Canada, 1: 385&ndash;390). Subspecies rejected by Moriarty and Cannatella (2004, Mol. Phylogenet. Evol. 30: 409&ndash;420).  \n\nNote on genus:  \nLemmon et al. (2007, Mol. Phylogenet. Evol. 44: 1068&ndash;1082) revised the *P. nigrita* group (*P. brimleyi, P. brachyphona, P. clarkii, P. feriarum, P. kalmi, P. maculata*, and *P. triseriata* and an unnamed species, which was subsequently named as *Pseudacris fouquettei*). Fouquette and Dubois (2014, Checklist N.A. Amph. Rept.) deployed a system of subgenera based on the work of Lemmon et al., placing the eastern species in the subgenus *Pseudacris* and the western members (*P. cadaverina, P. hypchondriaca, P. regilla*, and *P. sierra*) in the subgenus *Hyliola*, and the species *P. ocularis* and *P. crucifer* in the subgenus *Limnaoedus* but we have not adopted subgenera in this list.', 'michelle koo', 'Darrel R. Frost, David M. Green, Emily Moriarty Lemmon, Roy W. McDiarmid, and Joseph R. Mendelson III', '', 0, 0, 0),
(778, 'pseudacris', 'ocularis', '', 'little grass frog', '', '', '', 'anura', 'frogs', 'chorus frogs', '', 'anura', 'fitzinger', 'bosc and daudin', '{&quot;1843&quot;:&quot;1801&quot;}', '', 'Reviewed by Franz and Chantell (1978, Cat. Am. Amph. Rept. 209, as *Limnaoedus ocularis*), Jensen, (2005,in Lannoo, M. [ed.], Amph. Declines: 475&ndash;477), and Dodd (2013, Frogs U.S. and Canada, 1: 391&ndash;395).    \n\nNote on genus:  \nLemmon et al. (2007, Mol. Phylogenet. Evol. 44: 1068&ndash;1082) revised the *P. nigrita* group (*P. brimleyi, P. brachyphona, P. clarkii, P. feriarum, P. kalmi, P. maculata*, and *P. triseriata* and an unnamed species, which was subsequently named as *Pseudacris fouquettei*). Fouquette and Dubois (2014, Checklist N.A. Amph. Rept.) deployed a system of subgenera based on the work of Lemmon et al., placing the eastern species in the subgenus *Pseudacris* and the western members (*P. cadaverina, P. hypchondriaca, P. regilla*, and *P. sierra*) in the subgenus *Hyliola*, and the species *P. ocularis* and *P. crucifer* in the subgenus *Limnaoedus* but we have not adopted subgenera in this list.', 'michelle koo', 'Darrel R. Frost, David M. Green, Emily Moriarty Lemmon, Roy W. McDiarmid, and Joseph R. Mendelson III', '', 0, 0, 0),
(779, 'pseudacris', 'ornata', '', 'ornate chorus frog', '', '', '', 'anura', 'frogs', 'chorus frogs', '', 'anura', 'fitzinger', 'holbrook', '{&quot;1843&quot;:&quot;1836&quot;}', '', 'For discussion see Harper (1937, Am. Midl. Nat. 18: 260&ndash;272). Reviewed by Jensen (2005, in Lannoo, M. [ed.], Amph. Declines: 477&ndash;478), and Dodd (2013, Frogs U.S. and Canada, 1: 395&ndash;400).   \n\nNote on genus:  \nLemmon et al. (2007, Mol. Phylogenet. Evol. 44: 1068&ndash;1082) revised the *P. nigrita* group (*P. brimleyi, P. brachyphona, P. clarkii, P. feriarum, P. kalmi, P. maculata*, and *P. triseriata* and an unnamed species, which was subsequently named as *Pseudacris fouquettei*). Fouquette and Dubois (2014, Checklist N.A. Amph. Rept.) deployed a system of subgenera based on the work of Lemmon et al., placing the eastern species in the subgenus *Pseudacris* and the western members (*P. cadaverina, P. hypchondriaca, P. regilla*, and *P. sierra*) in the subgenus *Hyliola*, and the species *P. ocularis* and *P. crucifer* in the subgenus *Limnaoedus* but we have not adopted subgenera in this list.', 'michelle koo', 'Darrel R. Frost, David M. Green, Emily Moriarty Lemmon, Roy W. McDiarmid, and Joseph R. Mendelson III', '', 0, 0, 0),
(780, 'pseudacris', 'regilla', '', 'pacific treefrog', '', '', '', 'anura', 'frogs', 'chorus frogs', '', 'anura', 'fitzinger', 'baird and girard', '{&quot;1843&quot;:&quot;1852&quot;}', '', 'Recuero et al. (2006, Mol. Phylogenet. Evol. 39: 293&ndash;304) redelimited this species and revised its range. Rorabaugh and Lannoo (2005, in Lannoo, M. [ed.], Amph. Declines: 478&ndash;484) provided a detailed account that summarized the literature (in the sense of including *Pseudacris sierra* and *Pseudacris hypochondriaca*.  Dodd (2013, Frogs U.S. and Canada, 1: 400&ndash;416) also provided a review. \n\nNote on genus:  \nLemmon et al. (2007, Mol. Phylogenet. Evol. 44: 1068&ndash;1082) revised the *P. nigrita* group (*P. brimleyi, P. brachyphona, P. clarkii, P. feriarum, P. kalmi, P. maculata*, and *P. triseriata* and an unnamed species, which was subsequently named as *Pseudacris fouquettei*). Fouquette and Dubois (2014, Checklist N.A. Amph. Rept.) deployed a system of subgenera based on the work of Lemmon et al., placing the eastern species in the subgenus *Pseudacris* and the western members (*P. cadaverina, P. hypchondriaca, P. regilla*, and *P. sierra*) in the subgenus *Hyliola*, and the species *P. ocularis* and *P. crucifer* in the subgenus *Limnaoedus* but we have not adopted subgenera in this list.', 'michelle koo', 'Darrel R. Frost, David M. Green, Emily Moriarty Lemmon, Roy W. McDiarmid, and Joseph R. Mendelson III', '', 0, 0, 0),
(781, 'pseudacris', 'sierra', '', 'sierran treefrog', '', '', '', 'anura', 'frogs', 'chorus frogs', '', 'anura', 'fitzinger', 'jameson, mackey, and richmond', '{&quot;1843&quot;:&quot;1966&quot;}', '', 'Recognized as distinct from *P. regilla* by Recuero et al. (2006, Mol. Phylogenet. Evol. 39: 293&ndash;304; 2006, Mol. Phylogenet. Evol. 41: 511). See comment under *P. hypochondriaca*.  \n\nNote on genus:  \nLemmon et al. (2007, Mol. Phylogenet. Evol. 44: 1068&ndash;1082) revised the *P. nigrita* group (*P. brimleyi, P. brachyphona, P. clarkii, P. feriarum, P. kalmi, P. maculata*, and *P. triseriata* and an unnamed species, which was subsequently named as *Pseudacris fouquettei*). Fouquette and Dubois (2014, Checklist N.A. Amph. Rept.) deployed a system of subgenera based on the work of Lemmon et al., placing the eastern species in the subgenus *Pseudacris* and the western members (*P. cadaverina, P. hypchondriaca, P. regilla*, and *P. sierra*) in the subgenus *Hyliola*, and the species *P. ocularis* and *P. crucifer* in the subgenus *Limnaoedus* but we have not adopted subgenera in this list.', 'michelle koo', 'Darrel R. Frost, David M. Green, Emily Moriarty Lemmon, Roy W. McDiarmid, and Joseph R. Mendelson III', '', 0, 0, 0),
(782, 'pseudacris', 'streckeri', '', 'strecker&amp;#39;s chorus frog', '', '', '', 'anura', 'frogs', 'chorus frogs', '', 'anura', 'fitzinger', 'wright and wright', '{&quot;1843&quot;:&quot;1933&quot;}', '', 'Reviewed by Smith (1966, Cat. Am. Amph. Rept. 27), and Shepard, Brown, and Butterfield, (2005, in Lannoo, M. [ed.], Amph. Decline: 484&ndash;485) provided reviews in the sense of including *Pseudacris illinoensis*. Dodd (2013, Frogs U.S. and Canada, 1: 416&ndash;421) also provided a review. See comment under *Pseudacris illinoensis*.', 'michelle koo', 'Darrel R. Frost, David M. Green, Emily Moriarty Lemmon, Roy W. McDiarmid, and Joseph R. Mendelson III', '', 0, 0, 0),
(783, 'pseudacris', 'triseriata', '', 'western chorus frog', '', '', '', 'anura', 'frogs', 'chorus frogs', '', 'anura', 'fitzinger', 'wied-neuwied', '{&quot;1843&quot;:&quot;1838&quot;}', '', 'See comment under *P. maculata*. Lemmon et al. (2007, Mol. Phylogenet. Evol. 44: 1068&ndash;1082) revised the geographic limits of this species based on mitochondrial DNA evidence. Dodd (2013, Frogs U.S. and Canada, 1: 421&ndash;428) reviewed the species.', 'michelle koo', 'Darrel R. Frost, David M. Green, Emily Moriarty Lemmon, Roy W. McDiarmid, and Joseph R. Mendelson III', '', 0, 0, 0),
(784, 'rana', 'aurora', '', 'northern red-legged frog', '', '', '', 'anura', 'frogs', 'brown frogs', '', 'anura', 'linnaeus', 'baird and girard', '{&quot;1758&quot;:&quot;1852&quot;}', '', 'Reviewed by Altig and Dumas (1972, Cat. Am. Amph. Rept. 160, in the sense of including *R. draytonii*), Pearl (2005, in Lannoo, M. [ed.], Amph. Declines: 528&ndash;530), and Dodd (2013, Frogs U.S. and Canada, 2 : 687&ndash;697). Evidence of the distinctiveness of this species from *R. draytonii* was provided by Hayes and Miyamoto (1984, Copeia 1984: 1018&ndash;1022), Shaffer et al. (2004, Mol. Phylogenet. Evol. 13: 2667&ndash;2677), Conlon et al. (2006, Peptides 27: 1305&ndash;1312), and Pauly et al. (2008, J. Herpetol. 42: 668&ndash;679).    \n\nNote on genus:  \nThis large taxon of predominantly Eurasian frogs was redelimited by Frost et al. (2006, Bull. Am. Mus. Nat. Hist., 297, and Che et al. (2007, Mol. Phylogenet. Evol. 42: 1&ndash;13) to exclude a number of taxa (e.g., *Lithobates, Glandirana, Odorrana, Pelophylax*). See *Lithobates* for most North American species formerly associated with *Rana* and comments regarding taxonomy.', 'michelle koo', 'Darrel R. Frost, David M. Green, Emily Moriarty Lemmon, Roy W. McDiarmid, and Joseph R. Mendelson III', '', 0, 0, 0),
(785, 'rana', 'boylii', '', 'foothill yellow-legged frog', '', '', '', 'anura', 'frogs', 'brown frogs', '', 'anura', 'linnaeus', 'baird', '{&quot;1758&quot;:&quot;1854&quot;}', '', 'Reviewed by Zweifel (1968, Cat. Am. Amph. Rept. 71), Fellers (2005, in Lannoo, M. [ed.], Amph. Declines: 534&ndash;536), and Dodd (2013, Frogs U.S. and Canada, 2 : 697&ndash;707). Molecular study of geographic variation of this rapidly disappearing species should prove illuminating.  \n\nNote on genus:  \nThis large taxon of predominantly Eurasian frogs was redelimited by Frost et al. (2006, Bull. Am. Mus. Nat. Hist., 297, and Che et al. (2007, Mol. Phylogenet. Evol. 42: 1&ndash;13) to exclude a number of taxa (e.g., *Lithobates, Glandirana, Odorrana, Pelophylax*). See *Lithobates* for most North American species formerly associated with *Rana* and comments regarding taxonomy.', 'michelle koo', 'Darrel R. Frost, David M. Green, Emily Moriarty Lemmon, Roy W. McDiarmid, and Joseph R. Mendelson III', '', 0, 0, 0),
(786, 'rana', 'cascadae', '', 'cascades frog', '', '', '', 'anura', 'frogs', 'brown frogs', '', 'anura', 'linnaeus', 'slater', '{&quot;1758&quot;:&quot;1939&quot;}', '', 'Reviewed by Altig and Dumas (1971, Cat. Am. Amph. Rept. 105), Pearl and Adams (2005, in Lannoo, M. [ed.], Amph. Declines: 538&ndash;540), and Dodd (2013, Frogs U.S. and Canada, 2 : 707&ndash;715). The disjunct populations should be investigated with respect to call and molecular parameters.  \n\nNote on genus:  \nThis large taxon of predominantly Eurasian frogs was redelimited by Frost et al. (2006, Bull. Am. Mus. Nat. Hist., 297, and Che et al. (2007, Mol. Phylogenet. Evol. 42: 1&ndash;13) to exclude a number of taxa (e.g., *Lithobates, Glandirana, Odorrana, Pelophylax*). See *Lithobates* for most North American species formerly associated with *Rana* and comments regarding taxonomy.', 'michelle koo', 'Darrel R. Frost, David M. Green, Emily Moriarty Lemmon, Roy W. McDiarmid, and Joseph R. Mendelson III', '', 0, 0, 0),
(787, 'rana', 'draytonii', '', 'california red-legged frog', '', '', '', 'anura', 'frogs', 'brown frogs', '', 'anura', 'linnaeus', 'baird and girard', '{&quot;1758&quot;:&quot;1852&quot;}', '', 'See comment under *R. aurora*. Reviewed by Fellers (2005, in Lannoo, M. [ed.], Amph. Declines: 552&ndash;554) and Dodd (2013, Frogs U.S. and Canada, 2 : 715&ndash;722).   \n\nNote on genus:  \nThis large taxon of predominantly Eurasian frogs was redelimited by Frost et al. (2006, Bull. Am. Mus. Nat. Hist., 297, and Che et al. (2007, Mol. Phylogenet. Evol. 42: 1&ndash;13) to exclude a number of taxa (e.g., *Lithobates, Glandirana, Odorrana, Pelophylax*). See *Lithobates* for most North American species formerly associated with *Rana* and comments regarding taxonomy.', 'michelle koo', '', '', 0, 0, 0),
(788, 'rana', 'luteiventris', '', 'columbia spotted frog', '', '', '', 'anura', 'frogs', 'brown frogs', '', 'anura', 'linnaeus', 'thompson', '{&quot;1758&quot;:&quot;1913&quot;}', '', 'Green et al. (1996, Evolution 50: 374&ndash;390) and Cuellar (1996, Biogeographica 72: 145&ndash;150) suggested that *R. pretiosa* was composed of two sibling species. Subsequently Green et al. (1997, Copeia 1997: 1&ndash;8) recognized the eastern and northern form, *R. luteiventris*, as a species distinct from *R. pretiosa*. Reviewed by Reaser and Pilliod (2005, in Lannoo, M. [ed.], Amph. Declines: 559&ndash;563) and Dodd (2013, Frogs U.S. and Canada, 2: 723&ndash;732).   \n\nNote on genus:  \nThis large taxon of predominantly Eurasian frogs was redelimited by Frost et al. (2006, Bull. Am. Mus. Nat. Hist., 297, and Che et al. (2007, Mol. Phylogenet. Evol. 42: 1&ndash;13) to exclude a number of taxa (e.g., *Lithobates, Glandirana, Odorrana, Pelophylax*). See *Lithobates* for most North American species formerly associated with *Rana* and comments regarding taxonomy.', 'michelle koo', 'Darrel R. Frost, David M. Green, Emily Moriarty Lemmon, Roy W. McDiarmid, and Joseph R. Mendelson III', '', 0, 0, 0),
(789, 'rana', 'muscosa', '', 'southern mountain yellow-legged frog', '', '', '', 'anura', 'frogs', 'brown frogs', '', 'anura', 'linnaeus', 'camp', '{&quot;1758&quot;:&quot;1917&quot;}', '', 'Reviewed by Zweifel (1968, Cat. Am. Amph. Rept. 65), Vredenburg, Fellers, and Davidson (2005, in Lannoo, M. [ed.], Amph. Declines: 563&ndash;566), and Dodd (2013, Frogs U.S. and Canada, 2 : 733&ndash;739). Vredenburg et al. (2007, J. Zool. 271: 361&ndash;374) discussed the systematics of this species and its disappearance from large parts of its former range.', 'michelle koo', 'Darrel R. Frost, David M. Green, Emily Moriarty Lemmon, Roy W. McDiarmid, and Joseph R. Mendelson III', '', 0, 0, 0),
(790, 'rana', 'pretiosa', '', 'oregon spotted frog', '', '', '', 'anura', 'frogs', 'brown frogs', '', 'anura', 'linnaeus', 'baird and girard', '{&quot;1758&quot;:&quot;1853&quot;}', '', 'See comment under *R. luteiventris*. Reviewed by Pearl and Hayes (2005, in Lannoo, M. [ed.], Amph. Declines: 577&ndash;580) and Dodd (2013, Frogs U.S. and Canada, 2 : 739&ndash;747).', 'michelle koo', 'Darrel R. Frost, David M. Green, Emily Moriarty Lemmon, Roy W. McDiarmid, and Joseph R. Mendelson III', '', 0, 0, 0),
(791, 'rana', 'sierrae', '', 'sierra nevada yellow-legged frog', '', '', '', 'anura', 'frogs', 'brown frogs', '', 'anura', 'linnaeus', 'camp', '{&quot;1758&quot;:&quot;1917&quot;}', '', 'Vredenburg et al. (2007, J. Zool. 271: 361&ndash;374) recognized this species as distinct from *R. muscosa*. Reviewed by Dodd (2013, Frogs U.S. and Canada, 2 : 747&ndash;752).', 'michelle koo', 'Darrel R. Frost, David M. Green, Emily Moriarty Lemmon, Roy W. McDiarmid, and Joseph R. Mendelson III', '', 0, 0, 0),
(792, 'rhinella', 'marina', '', 'cane toad', '', '', '', 'anura', 'frogs', 'south american toads', '', 'anura', 'fitzinger', 'linnaeus', '{&quot;1826&quot;:&quot;1758&quot;}', '', 'Reviewed by Easteal (1986, Cat. Am. Amph. Rept. 395, as *Bufo marinus*). Hero and Stoneham (2005, in Lannoo, M. [ed.], Amph. Declines: 417&ndash;422, as *Bufo marinus*) and Dodd (2013, Frogs U.S. and Canada, 1: 186&ndash;191), provided a detailed account for the USA. Vallinoto et al. (2010, Zool. Scripta 39: 128&ndash;140) provided molecular evidence that the North and Central American population may be a distinct species from the South American populations (at least one of which bears the name *R. marina*), which suggests that the name applied to the USA population likely will change as relationships become more clear.  \n\n\nNote on genus:  \nThis genus of predominantly South American toads was redelimited by Chaparro et al. (2007, Herpetologica 63: 203&ndash;212) to reflect the phylogenetic results of Pramuk (2006, Zool. J. Linn. Soc. 146: 407&ndash;452). Van Bocxlaer et al. (2010, Science 327: 679&ndash;682) suggested that *Rhinella* is only distantly related to North American toads of the genera *Incilius* and *Anaxyrus*. See comment under *Anaxyrus*, regarding the treatment of this genus as a subgenus by some.', 'michelle koo', 'Darrel R. Frost, David M. Green, Emily Moriarty Lemmon, Roy W. McDiarmid, and Joseph R. Mendelson III', '', 0, 0, 0),
(793, 'rhinophrynus', 'dorsalis', '', 'burrowing toad', '', '', '', 'anura', 'frogs', 'burrowing toads', '', 'anura', 'dum', 'dum', '{&quot;1841&quot;:&quot;1841&quot;}', '', 'Geographic variation has not been studied in any detail and cryptic lineages are a possibility. Reviewed by Fouquette (1969, Cat. Am. Amph. Rept. 78) and Fouquette (2005, in Lannoo, M. [ed.], Amph. Declines: 599&ndash;600).', 'michelle koo', 'Darrel R. Frost, David M. Green, Emily Moriarty Lemmon, Roy W. McDiarmid, and Joseph R. Mendelson III', '', 0, 0, 0),
(794, 'scaphiopus', 'couchii', '', 'couch&amp;#39;s spadefoot', '', '', '', 'anura', 'frogs', 'north american spadefoots', '', 'anura', 'holbrook', 'baird', '{&quot;1836&quot;:&quot;1854&quot;}', '', 'Reviewed by Wasserman (1970, Cat. Am. Amph. Rept. 85), Morey (2005, in Lannoo, M. [ed.], Amph. Declines: 508&ndash;511), and Dodd (2013, Frogs U.S. and Canada, 2 : 753&ndash;760). Geographic variation is poorly documented.', 'michelle koo', 'Darrel R. Frost, David M. Green, Emily Moriarty Lemmon, Roy W. McDiarmid, and Joseph R. Mendelson III', '', 0, 0, 0),
(795, 'scaphiopus', 'holbrookii', '', 'eastern spadefoot', '', '', '', 'anura', 'frogs', 'north american spadefoots', '', 'anura', 'holbrook', 'harlan', '{&quot;1836&quot;:&quot;1835&quot;}', '', 'Reviewed by Wasserman (1968, Cat. Am. Amph. Rept. 70, as *Scaphiopus h. holbrookii*), Palis (2005, in Lannoo, M. [ed.], Amph. Declines: 511&ndash;512), and Dodd (2013, Frogs U.S. and Canada, 2: 772&ndash;776).', 'michelle koo', 'Darrel R. Frost, David M. Green, Emily Moriarty Lemmon, Roy W. McDiarmid, and Joseph R. Mendelson III', '', 0, 0, 0),
