(818, 'aspidoscelis', 'hyperythra', 'beldingi', 'belding&amp;#39;s orange throated whiptail ', '', '', '', 'squamata ', 'lizards', 'whiptails', '', 'squamata ', 'fitzinger', 'stejneger', '{&quot;1843&quot;:&quot;1894&quot;}', '', 'According to previous taxonomies (e.g., Maslin and Secoy, 1986, Contrib. Zool. Univ.Colorado Mus. 1: 1&ndash;60; Wright, 1993, in J. W. Wright and L. J. Vitt [eds.], Biology of Whiptail Lizards [Genus Cnemidophorus], Oklahoma Mus. Nat. Hist., Pp. 27&ndash;81), the subspecies Aspidoscelis hyperythra beldingi occurs in the United States. ', 'kelsey lyberger', 'Kevin de Quieroz (Chair) and Tod W. Reeder', '', 0, 0, 0),
(819, 'aspidoscelis', 'inornata', '', 'little striped whiptail', '', '', '', 'squamata', 'lizards', 'whiptails', '', 'squamata', 'fitzinger', 'baird', '{&quot;1843&quot;:&quot;1859 \\&quot;1858\\&quot;&quot;}', '', 'Taxonomy for Aspidoscelis follows Maslin and Secoy (1986, Contrib. Zool. Univ. Colorado Mus. 1: 1&ndash;60) and Wright (1993, in J. W. Wright and L. J. Vitt [eds.], Biology of Whiptail Lizards [Genus Cnemidophorus], Oklahoma Mus. Nat. Hist., Pp. 27&ndash;81). Wright and Lowe (1993, J. Arizona-Nevada Acad. Sci. 27: 129&ndash;157) recognized six subspecies of *Aspidoscelis inornata* in the United States.  Collins (1997, SSAR Herpetol. Circ. 25), treated three of them, *arizonae, gypsi*, and *pai*, as separate species, presumably because they are geographically separated and morphologically distinguishable both from one another and from the other subspecies of *A. inornata* recognized by Wright and Lowe (op. cit.).', 'kelsey lyberger', 'Kevin de Quieroz (Chair) and Tod W. Reeder', '', 0, 0, 0),
(820, 'aspidoscelis', 'inornata', 'gypsi', 'little white whiptail', '', '', '', 'squamata', 'lizards', 'whiptails', '', 'squamata', 'fitzinger', 'wright and lowe', '{&quot;1843&quot;:&quot;1993&quot;}', '', 'Taxonomy for Aspidoscelis follows Maslin and Secoy (1986, Contrib. Zool. Univ. Colorado Mus. 1: 1&ndash;60) and Wright (1993, in J. W. Wright and L. J. Vitt [eds.], Biology of Whiptail Lizards [Genus Cnemidophorus], Oklahoma Mus. Nat. Hist., Pp. 27&ndash;81). Rosenblum and Harmon (2010, Evolution 65: 946&ndash;960), in a study based on nuclear and mitochondrial DNA, coloration, and body size and proportions, concluded that although whiptails from the gypsum sands had diverged more from their dark soil counterparts in terms of body size and shape than sympatric earless and fence lizards (see notes on Holbrookia maculata ruthveni and Sceloporus cowlesi), the genetic data indicate that the whiptails are failing to speciate.  This conclusion suggests that it is more appropriate to recognize the taxon not as a species (as proposed by Collins, 1997, SSAR Herpetol. Circ. 25) but as a subspecies of A. inornata (as originally proposed by Wright and Lowe, 1993, J. Arizona-Nevada Acad. Sci. 27: 129&ndash;157).', 'kelsey lyberger', 'Kevin de Quieroz (Chair) and Tod W. Reeder', '', 0, 0, 0),
(821, 'aspidoscelis', 'inornata', 'llanuras', 'plains striped whiptail', '', '', '', 'squamata', 'lizards', 'whiptails', '', 'squamata', 'fitzinger', 'wright and lowe', '{&quot;1843&quot;:&quot;1993&quot;}', '', 'Taxonomy for Aspidoscelis follows Maslin and Secoy (1986, Contrib. Zool. Univ. Colorado Mus. 1: 1&ndash;60) and Wright (1993, in J. W. Wright and L. J. Vitt [eds.], Biology of Whiptail Lizards [Genus Cnemidophorus], Oklahoma Mus. Nat. Hist., Pp. 27&ndash;81). Walker et al. (1996, J. Herpetol. 30: 271&ndash;275) called into question some of the characters used by Wright and Lowe (1993, J. Arizona-Nevada Acad. Sci. 27: 129&ndash;157) to separate Aspidoscelis inornata llanuras from A. i. heptagramma but did not explicitly treat the names as synonyms.', 'kelsey lyberger', 'Kevin de Quieroz (Chair) and Tod W. Reeder', '', 0, 0, 0),
(822, 'aspidoscelis', 'laredoensis', '', 'laredo striped whiptail', '', '', '', 'squamata', 'lizards', 'whiptails', '', 'squamata', 'fitzinger', 'mckinney,kay and anderson', '{&quot;1843&quot;:&quot;1973&quot;}', '', 'Taxonomy for Aspidoscelis follows Maslin and Secoy (1986, Contrib. Zool. Univ. Colorado Mus. 1: 1&ndash;60) and Wright (1993, in J. W. Wright and L. J. Vitt [eds.], Biology of Whiptail Lizards [Genus Cnemidophorus], Oklahoma Mus. Nat. Hist., Pp. 27&ndash;81). Abuhteba et al. (2001, Copeia 2001: 262&ndash;266) interpreted histoincompatibility between the members of two pattern classes within Aspidoscelis laredoensis as evidence for separate hybrid origins of the corresponding clones.  The authors noted that two of them are planning to restrict the name A. laredoensis to one of the clones and propose a new species name for the other.', 'kelsey lyberger', 'Kevin de Quieroz (Chair) and Tod W. Reeder', '', 0, 0, 0),
(823, 'aspidoscelis', 'marmorata', '', 'marbled whiptail', '', '', '', 'squamata', 'lizards', 'whiptails', '', 'squamata', 'fitzinger', 'baird and girard', '{&quot;1843&quot;:&quot;1852&quot;}', '', 'Taxonomy for Aspidoscelis follows Maslin and Secoy (1986, Contrib. Zool. Univ. Colorado Mus. 1: 1&ndash;60) and Wright (1993, in J. W. Wright and L. J. Vitt [eds.], Biology of Whiptail Lizards [Genus Cnemidophorus], Oklahoma Mus. Nat. Hist., Pp. 27&ndash;81). Dessauer and Cole (1991, Copeia 1991: 622&ndash;637; see also Dessauer et al., 2000, Bull. Am. Mus. Nat. Hist. 246: 1&ndash;148) presented evidence of both differentiation and interbreeding between A. marmorata and A. tigris along a transect near the southern part of the border between Arizona and New Mexico, including a narrow (3 km) hybrid zone in which hybrid indices based on color patterns and allele frequencies changed abruptly in concordant step clines.  Although those authors interpreted their data as reflecting incomplete speciation between the two forms (i.e., a single species), the same data can be interpreted alternatively as reflecting largely separate gene pools (i.e., two species).  Following the terminology of de Queiroz (1998, in D. J. Howard and S. H. Berlocher [eds.], Endless Forms:  Species and Speciation, Oxford University Press, Pp. 57&ndash;75), they are here considered incompletely separated species.', 'kelsey lyberger', 'Kevin de Quieroz (Chair) and Tod W. Reeder', '', 0, 0, 0),
(824, 'aspidoscelis', 'marmorata', 'marmorata', 'western marbed whiptail', '', '', '', 'squamata', 'lizards', 'whiptails', '', 'squamata', 'fitzinger', 'baird and girard', '{&quot;1843&quot;:&quot;1852&quot;}', '', 'Taxonomy for Aspidoscelis follows Maslin and Secoy (1986, Contrib. Zool. Univ. Colorado Mus. 1: 1&ndash;60) and Wright (1993, in J. W. Wright and L. J. Vitt [eds.], Biology of Whiptail Lizards [Genus Cnemidophorus], Oklahoma Mus. Nat. Hist., Pp. 27&ndash;81). Taylor et al. (2001, Am. Mus. Novit. 3345: 1&ndash;65) presented evidence for hybridization between A. tesselata and A. marmorata, but there is no indication that this hybridization has produced a new hybrid species.', 'kelsey lyberger', 'Kevin de Quieroz (Chair) and Tod W. Reeder', '', 0, 0, 0),
(825, 'aspidoscelis', 'marmorata', 'reticuloriens', 'eastern marbled whiptail', '', '', '', 'squamata', 'lizards', 'whiptails', '', 'squamata', 'fitzinger', 'vance', '{&quot;1843&quot;:&quot;1978&quot;}', '', 'Taxonomy for Aspidoscelis follows Maslin and Secoy (1986, Contrib. Zool. Univ. Colorado Mus. 1: 1&ndash;60) and Wright (1993, in J. W. Wright and L. J. Vitt [eds.], Biology of Whiptail Lizards [Genus Cnemidophorus], Oklahoma Mus. Nat. Hist., Pp. 27&ndash;81). Taylor et al. (2001, Am. Mus. Novit. 3345: 1&ndash;65) presented evidence for hybridization between A. tesselata and A. marmorata, but there is no indication that this hybridization has produced a new hybrid species.', 'kelsey lyberger', 'Kevin de Quieroz (Chair) and Tod W. Reeder', '', 0, 0, 0);
