(845, 'aspidoscelis', 'velox', '', 'plateau striped whiptail (unisexual)', '', '', '', 'squamata', 'lizards', 'whiptails', '', 'squamata', 'fitzinger', 'springer', '{&quot;1843&quot;:&quot;1928&quot;}', '', 'Taxonomy for Aspidoscelis follows Maslin and Secoy (1986, Contrib. Zool. Univ. Colorado Mus. 1: 1&ndash;60) and Wright (1993, in J. W. Wright and L. J. Vitt [eds.], Biology of Whiptail Lizards [Genus Cnemidophorus], Oklahoma Mus. Nat. Hist., Pp. 27&ndash;81). Maslin and Secoy (1986, Contrib. Zool. Univ. Colorado Mus. 1: 1&ndash;60) treated the name Aspidoscelis (sackii) innotata as a synonym of A. velox, but Wright (1993, in J. W. Wright and L. J. Vitt [eds.], Biology of Whiptail Lizards [Genus Cnemidophorus], Oklahoma Mus. Nat. Hist., Pp. 27&ndash;81) applied the name A. velox to populations of triploid parthenogens and treated A. innotata as the name of a separate diploid species.  Cuellar (1977, Evolution 31: 24&ndash;31) found histoincompatibility (rejection of skin grafts) between A. velox-like lizards from Colorado, New Mexico, and Utah, which Cuellar and Wright (1992, C. R. Soc. Biogeogr. 68: 157&ndash;160) interpreted as potential evidence for different ploidy levels.  The type locality of A. velox is in Arizona, while that of A. innotata is in Utah, and lizards from New Mexico are known to be triploid (Neaves, 1969, J. Exper. Zool. 171: 175&ndash;184; Dessauer and Cole, 1989, in R. M. Dawley and J. P. Bogart [eds.], Evolution and Ecology of Unisexual Vertebrates, New York State Museum, Pp. 49&ndash;71).  If lizards from the type locality of A. innotata turn out to be diploid, it would be reasonable to recognize a separate diploid species and apply the name A. innotata (Plateau Unspotted Whiptail) to it.', 'kelsey lyberger', 'Kevin de Quieroz (Chair) and Tod W. Reeder', '', 0, 0, 0),
