(956, 'sceloporus', 'clarkii', 'vallaris', 'plateau spiny lizard', '', '', '', 'squamata ', 'lizards', 'spiny lizards', '', 'squamata ', 'wiegmann', 'shannon and urbano', '{&quot;1828&quot;:&quot;1954&quot;}', '', 'Taxonomy for Sceloporus follows Schmidt (1953, A Check List of North American Amphibians and Reptiles, Univ. Chicago Press, Chicago)', 'kelsey lyberger', 'Kevin de Quieroz (Chair) and Tod W. Reeder', '', 0, 0, 0),
(957, 'sceloporus', 'consobrinus', '', 'prairie lizard', '', '', '', 'squamata ', 'lizards', 'spiny lizards', '', 'squamata ', 'wiegmann', 'baird and girard', '{&quot;1828&quot;:&quot;1853&quot;}', '', 'Taxonomy for Sceloporus follows Schmidt (1953, A Check List of North American Amphibians and Reptiles, Univ. Chicago Press, Chicago). Leach&eacute; and Reeder (2002, Syst. Biol. 51: 44&ndash;68) noted that the name S. thayerii Baird and Girard 1852 (type locality:  Indianola, Calhoun Co., TX) may turn out to be the correct name of this species and that populations east of the Mississippi River along the Gulf Coast may represent a separate species.', 'kelsey lyberger', 'Kevin de Quieroz (Chair) and Tod W. Reeder', '', 0, 0, 0),
(958, 'sceloporus', 'cowlesi', '', 'southwestern fence lizard', '', '', '', 'squamata ', 'lizards', 'spiny lizards', '', 'squamata ', 'wiegmann', 'lowe and norris', '{&quot;1828&quot;:&quot;1956&quot;}', '', 'Taxonomy for Sceloporus follows Schmidt (1953, A Check List of North American Amphibians and Reptiles, Univ. Chicago Press, Chicago). Leach&eacute; and Reeder (2002, Syst. Biol. 51: 44&ndash;68) applied the name S. cowlesi to the populations from roughly the region of the Chihuahuan Desert.  Although the name S. cowlesi was originally applied to light colored lizards from the White Sands of New Mexico, Leach&eacute; and Reeder (op. cit.) presented evidence that mtDNA haplotypes from White Sands lizards are deeply nested within a clade of haplotypes from geographically proximate darker lizards, and Rosenblum (2006, Am. Nat. 167: 1&ndash;15) found both phylogenetic mixing of haplotypes between light and dark forms and evidence of gene flow between them.  Rosenblum and Harmon (2010, Evolution 65: 946&ndash;960) found that fence lizards from the White Sands exhibited discordant patterns of morphological and genetic dfferentiation from their counterparts on adjacent darker soils and concluded that the populations have made incomplete progress toward speciation.  Leach&eacute; and Cole (2007, Mol. Ecol. 16: 1035&ndash;1054) presented evidence for hybridization between S. cowlesi and S. tristichus.', 'kelsey lyberger', 'Kevin de Quieroz (Chair) and Tod W. Reeder', '', 0, 0, 0),
(959, 'sceloporus', 'cyanogenys', '', 'blue spiny lizard', '', '', '', 'squamata ', 'lizards', 'spiny lizards', '', 'squamata ', 'wiegmann', 'cope', '{&quot;1828&quot;:&quot;1956&quot;}', '', 'Taxonomy for Sceloporus follows Schmidt (1953, A Check List of North American Amphibians and Reptiles, Univ. Chicago Press, Chicago). Olson (1987, Bull. Maryland Herpetol. Soc. 23: 158&ndash;167) treated Sceloporus cyanogenys as a subspecies of S. serrifer based on apparent integrades between the former species and S. serrifer plioporus.  Mart&iacute;nez-M&eacute;ndez and M&eacute;ndez de la Cruz (2007, Zootaxa 1609: 53&ndash;68) inferred S. serrifer plioporus and S. cyanogenys to form a mtDNA clade; however, that clade was relatively distantly related to S. serrifer serrifer and S. serrifer prezygus haplotypes (see also Wiens et al., 2010, Mol. Phylogenet. Evol. 54: 150&ndash;161).  Therefore, they synonymized the name S. s. plioporus with S. cyanogenys, retaining S. serrifer for a species that occurs south and east of the Isthmus of Tehuantepec.  ', 'kelsey lyberger', 'Kevin de Quieroz (Chair) and Tod W. Reeder', '', 0, 0, 0),
(960, 'sceloporus', 'graciosus', '', 'common sagebrush lizard', '', '', '', 'squamata ', 'lizards', 'spiny lizards', '', 'squamata ', 'wiegmann', 'baird and girard', '{&quot;1828&quot;:&quot;1852&quot;}', '', 'Taxonomy for Sceloporus follows Schmidt (1953, A Check List of North American Amphibians and Reptiles, Univ. Chicago Press, Chicago) . Chan et al. (2013, Zootaxa 3664: 312&ndash;320) found that the currently recongnized subspecies of S. graciosus are incongruent with mitochondrial haplotype clades, which often exhibit relatively deep divergences between geographically proximate samples, and that S. graciosus is paraphyletic relative to S. arenicolus.  Although these findings suggest that S. graciosus is in need of taxonomic revision, those authors did not propose any taxonomic changes.', 'kelsey lyberger', 'Kevin de Quieroz (Chair) and Tod W. Reeder', '', 0, 0, 0),
(961, 'sceloporus', 'graciosus', 'gracilis', 'western sagebrush lizard', '', '', '', 'squamata ', 'lizards', 'spiny lizards', '', 'squamata ', 'wiegmann', 'baird and girard', '{&quot;1828&quot;:&quot;1852&quot;}', '', 'Taxonomy for Sceloporus follows Schmidt (1953, A Check List of North American Amphibians and Reptiles, Univ. Chicago Press, Chicago). Chan et al. (2013, Zootaxa 3664: 312&ndash;320) found that the currently recongnized subspecies of S. graciosus are incongruent with mitochondrial haplotype clades, which often exhibit relatively deep divergences between geographically proximate samples, and that S. graciosus is paraphyletic relative to S. arenicolus.  Although these findings suggest that S. graciosus is in need of taxonomic revision, those authors did not propose any taxonomic changes.', 'kelsey lyberger', 'Kevin de Quieroz (Chair) and Tod W. Reeder', '', 0, 0, 0),
(962, 'sceloporus', 'graciosus', 'graciosus', 'northern sagebrush lizard', '', '', '', 'squamata ', 'lizards', 'spiny lizards', '', 'squamata ', 'wiegmann', 'baird and girard', '{"1828": "1852"}', '', '', NULL, NULL, '', 0, 0, 0),
(963, 'sceloporus', 'graciosus', 'vandenburgianus', 'southern sagebrush lizard', '', '', '', 'squamata ', 'lizards', 'spiny lizards', '', 'squamata ', 'wiegmann', 'cope', '{&quot;1828&quot;:&quot;1896&quot;}', '', 'Taxonomy for Sceloporus follows Schmidt (1953, A Check List of North American Amphibians and Reptiles, Univ. Chicago Press, Chicago). Censky (1986, Cat. Am. Amph. Rept. 386) treated Sceloporus graciosus vandenburgianus as a subspecies of S. graciosus, but Collins (1991, Herpetol. Rev. 22: 42&ndash;43) proposed recognizing this taxon as a species, S. vandenburgianus.  Wiens and Reeder (1997, Herpetol. Monog. 11: 1&ndash;101) followed Collins&rsquo;s proposal but noted the morphological similarity and geographic proximity of this taxon to populations of S. graciosus gracilis.  Chan et al. (2013, Zootaxa 3664: 312&ndash;320) found that S. g. vandenburgianus was mitochondrially distinct from S. g. gracilis and paraphyletic relative to a clade formed by eastern populations of S. g. graciosus and S. arenicolus.  We have retained vandenburgianus as a subspecies pending a detailed analysis of geographic variation in S. graciosus.', 'kelsey lyberger', 'Kevin de Quieroz (Chair) and Tod W. Reeder', '', 0, 0, 0),
(964, 'sceloporus', 'grammicus', '', 'graphic spiny lizard', '', '', '', 'squamata ', 'lizards', 'spiny lizards', '', 'squamata ', 'wiegmann', 'wiegmann', '{&quot;1828&quot;:&quot;1828&quot;}', '', 'Taxonomy for Sceloporus follows Schmidt (1953, A Check List of North American Amphibians and Reptiles, Univ. Chicago Press, Chicago). Lizards currently referred to Sceloporus grammicus form a complex series of chromosome races that likely represent multiple species (Sites, 1983, Evolution 37: 38&ndash;53; Ar&eacute;valo et al., 1991, Herpetol. Monog. 5: 79&ndash;115).  A detailed phylogeographic study of this species complex is sorely needed.', 'kelsey lyberger', 'Kevin de Quieroz (Chair) and Tod W. Reeder', '', 0, 0, 0),
(965, 'sceloporus', 'grammicus', 'microlepidotus', 'mesquite lizard', '', '', '', 'squamata ', 'lizards', 'spiny lizards', '', 'squamata ', 'wiegmann', 'wiegmann', '{&quot;1828&quot;:&quot;1828&quot;}', '', 'Taxonomy for Sceloporus follows Schmidt (1953, A Check List of North American Amphibians and Reptiles, Univ. Chicago Press, Chicago). Lizards currently referred to Sceloporus grammicus form a complex series of chromosome races that likely represent multiple species (Sites, 1983, Evolution 37: 38&ndash;53; Ar&eacute;valo et al., 1991, Herpetol. Monog. 5: 79&ndash;115).  A detailed phylogeographic study of this species complex is sorely needed.', 'kelsey lyberger', 'Kevin de Quieroz (Chair) and Tod W. Reeder', '', 0, 0, 0),
(966, 'sceloporus', 'jarrovii', '', 'yarrow&amp;#39;s spiny lizard', '', '', '', 'squamata ', 'lizards', 'spiny lizards', '', 'squamata ', 'wiegmann', 'cope, in yarrow', '{&quot;1828&quot;:&quot;1875&quot;}', '', 'Taxonomy for Sceloporus follows Schmidt (1953, A Check List of North American Amphibians and Reptiles, Univ. Chicago Press, Chicago). Wiens et al. (1999, Evolution 53: 1884&ndash;1897; restriction of the name S. jarrovii to one of five inferred species formerly referred to by that name)', 'kelsey lyberger', 'Kevin de Quieroz (Chair) and Tod W. Reeder', '', 0, 0, 0),
(967, 'sceloporus', 'magister', '', 'desert spiny lizard', '', '', '', 'squamata ', 'lizards', 'spiny lizards', '', 'squamata ', 'wiegmann', 'hallowell', '{&quot;1828&quot;:&quot;1854&quot;}', '', 'Taxonomy for Sceloporus follows Schmidt (1953, A Check List of North American Amphibians and Reptiles, Univ. Chicago Press, Chicago). Leach&eacute; and Mulcahy (2007, Mol. Ecol. 16: 5216&ndash;5233) found evidence of asymmetrical gene flow between S. magister and both S. bimaculosus and S. uniformis, with S. magister acting as a genetic &ldquo;sink&rdquo;.  Because these lineages show evidence of both separation (with divergence) and ongoing asymmetrical gene flow, they can be considered partially separated species.  Leach&eacute; and Mulcahy (op. cit.) also identified a fourth potentially separate lineage in northeastern Baja California (currently unnamed).  Schulte et al. (2006, Mol. Phylogenet. Evol. 39: 873&ndash;880) recognized the subspecies S. m. magister and S. m. cephaloflavus because their single sample from the Colorado Plateau (assumed to represent the subspecies S. m. cephaloflavus) was inferred to be the sister group of the samples representing S. m. magister.  Leach&eacute; and Mulcahy (op. cit.), however, found that specimens from closer to the type locality of S. m. cephaloflavus were part of S. uniformis rather than S. magister; consequently, we have not recognized subspecies within S. magister.', 'kelsey lyberger', 'Kevin de Quieroz (Chair) and Tod W. Reeder', '', 0, 0, 0),
